body:
The error message means onnx model input x1 does not have type information, which is required according to onnx spec.

Could you double check that the onnx model is generated correctly?

x1 is not an input to the model, but an edge in a model local function:
```  
func (x) => (y) {
    x1 = local.f1(x)
    y = local.f2(x1)
}
```
Is there a way to define types for input/outputs of f1 and f2 (functions)?

issue.title: Re-implment the function support in onnxruntime

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Description**: Currently the implementation of function support in onnxruntime is quite confusion. There are some history reasons. The initial implementation of "Function" was introduced to onnxruntime before the "Function" concept introduce to onnx, originally it is just for the fusion. Later, people try to leverage the same code to handle the functions in onnx. Since we have more and more trick cases in onnx function, the implementation become very mess. This PR is to re-implement the function support and make it clearer.

Today there are three cases you will have function introduced:
1. an onnx operator that has function body
2. a model local function
3. a function created by onnxruntime (for fusion)
(#3 will be deprecated soon, please refer to PR #10632)

Today, ONNX function doesn't support recursive. Therefore, in ONNXRuntime, we don't need to introduce the "Function Call" convention, we just have two ways to run the function: use an optimized kernel for the whole function, or inline the function. Based on this assumption, the design is:

1. during model loading phase, load all the model local function, generated a schema for those local functions and make sure it has a type/shape inference function attached.  
2. When a node in ORT graph refer to a local function, refer it to the generated schema in the model.
3. Please note that onnx "function" is not a real function in programming language, it is more like a "function template" that haven't instantiated yet. In model loading phase, we only need to validate the graph and resolve type/shapes, there is no need to instantiate the function body.
4. During graph partition, if there is no optimized kernel assigned to the function node, instantiate the function body on the node, then inline it to the main graph.

This PR will fix issue: #10250 

There are still some codes may need further PRs to clean up.

body: I can confirm that this issue is resolved with the above PR. Thank you

issue.title: Attributes in nested function calls are zeroed out

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Describe the bug**

Attributes in nested local function calls (referred to with `ref_attr`) are zeroed out, causing wrong results in inference.

**Urgency**

The standard is not fully supported and produces unexpected behaviour. 
I guess since this is a rather simple bug it's not a very often used feature though.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): 
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): binary, conda-forge
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.12.1
- ONNX version: 1.11.0
- Python version: 3.10.5

**To Reproduce**

The following test should pass, but it doesn't:

```py
m = onnx.parser.parse('''
<
  ir_version: 8,
  opset_import: [ "" : 14, "local" : 1],
  model_version: 1
>
agraph (int64[H] x) => (int64[H] y)
{
    y = local.func <outer = 1> (x)
}

<
  opset_import: [ "" : 14 ],
  domain: "local",
  doc_string: "function 1"
>
f1 <inner> (x) => (y) {
    c = Constant<value_int: int = @inner>()
    y = Add(x, c)
}

<
  opset_import: [ "" : 14, "local" : 1 ],
  domain: "local",
  doc_string: "Preprocessing function."
>
func <outer> (x) => (y) {
    y = local.f1 <inner: int = @outer> (x)
}
''')

print(m)
onnx.checker.check_model(m)
session = onnxruntime.InferenceSession(m.SerializeToString())

x = numpy.array([0, 0, 0], dtype=numpy.int64)
y = numpy.array([1, 1, 1], dtype=numpy.int64)
assert (session.run(None, {'x': x})[0] == y).all()
```

**Expected behavior**

The assert statement should pass. Behaviour should be equivalent to inlining the attribute by writing `<inner: int = 1>` instead of `<inner: int = @outer>`, but then the check does pass.
 
**Additional context**

Related to the introduced function spec rewrite https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/10250, which fixed a similar bug, but without presence of attributes (which are also in the standard).

I'm quite sure there's further issues here related to failing type inference (nested function calls where attributes are passed produce errors like `Node (_0x14ab9bc40_<snip>) output arg (_0x14ab9bc40_<snip>) type inference failed`), but I leave that to another report.
